Five truths about terrorism
SÃO PAULO – American policy is being held hostage by terrorism.
In December 2015, polls indicated that one out of every six Americans, or approximately 16% of the population, now placed terrorism at the top of the country's problems – an increase of 3% in just one month.
For ten years, no group of Americans had been as concerned about terrorism as they were then, although their numbers were still far below the 46% recorded immediately following the September 11, 2001 attacks.
The consequences of this public opinion shift were particularly felt during the Republican primary for the presidential election.
La candidature de Donald Trump, dont la rhétorique anti-musulmans est particulièrement enflammée (sinon incendiaire), en a sans aucun doute profité.
Certains hommes politiques s'autorisent à parler de la bataille contre le terrorisme comme de la « Troisième Guerre mondiale ».
Le terrorisme est un problème pour les États-Unis, comme l'a montré l'attentat de San Bernardino, en Californie, au mois de décembre de l'année dernière.
Mais dont les candidats à l'élection présidentielle, tout comme certains médias, adeptes du vieil adage « si ça saigne, ça fait la une », ont exagéré les proportions.
Pour replacer le terrorisme dans sa véritable perspective, les Américains devraient – comme d'autres – avoir en tête les considérations suivantes :
The terrorism is a kind of theater.
Terrorists are more worried about holding attention and dominating political news than the number of their victims themselves.
ISIS takes great care with its staging.
The barbaric decapitations broadcast on social media are meant to destabilize and scandalize—and thus to monopolize attention.
Overexaggerating their consequences and making big headlines with each terrorist action is playing the terrorists' game.
Le terrorisme n’est pas la plus grave menace pesant sur les populations des pays développés.
Le terrorisme tue beaucoup moins que les accidents de la route ou que la cigarette.
De ce point de vue, le terrorisme n’est même pas une véritable menace – ni majeure, ni mineure.
On a plus de chances d’être frappé par la foudre que d’être tué par un terroriste.
La probabilité qu’un citoyen américain soit assassiné par un terroriste est, selon les experts, d’une unité sur 3,5 millions.
Americans are more likely to die in their bathtub (one in 950,000), from an accident involving household appliances (one in 1.5 million), by a deer or elk crossing the road (one in 2 million), or in a commercial airline crash (one in 2.9 million).
Six thousand Americans die each year from texting and talking on their phone while driving.
This is several hundred times the number who die from terrorism.
Radical Islamic terrorism kills fewer Americans than workplace attacks or mass shootings at universities or schools.
Terrorism is not World War III.
The global terrorism is not new.
It often takes a generation to extinguish a wave of terrorism.
At the beginning of the 20th century, the anarchist movement killed a number of heads of state in the name of utopian ideals.
In the 1960s and 1970s, the Red Brigades and the Red Army Faction, which emerged from the 'autonomous' left, hijacked planes outside national borders and kidnapped or killed business leaders or political figures (but also ordinary citizens).
Today's jihadist extremists are an old political phenomenon draped in a religious guise.
<s>Many of their leaders are not fundamentalists in the traditional sense, but people whose identity has been destroyed by globalization, seeking meaning in the imaginary and pure community of an Islamic caliphate.
<s>It will take time and effort to defeat them, but the E.I.'s restrictive nature limits its appeal.
<s>Its sectarian attacks already prevent it from addressing all Muslims, let alone Hindus, Christians, or other believers.
<s>The E.I. will eventually be defeated, just as transnational terrorism that preceded it has been.
<s>Terrorism is like jujitsu.
The weaker of the two adversaries uses the power of the stronger to defeat them.
No terrorist organization has the power of a state, and few terrorist movements have succeeded in overthrowing one.
But if they manage to shock and provoke enough citizens of a state to push them into futile actions, they can hope to gain the upper hand.
In 2001, Al-Qaeda managed to draw the Americans to Afghanistan.
The E.I. was born from the ruins of the U.S.-led invasion of Iraq, which followed the intervention in Afghanistan.
Pour defeat terrorism, you need smart power.
Smart power is capable of combining the coercive power (hard power) of the army and the police with the influence power (soft power) of attraction and persuasion.
Influence power is also necessary if we want to vaccinate those on the periphery whom the irreducibles seek to recruit.
That is why the attention given to the narrative of events and how U.S. actions are commented on on social networks is as important and necessary as precision aerial strikes.
The rhetoric of confrontation, which points fingers at Muslims and alienates good will that would allow us to obtain crucial information, puts us all in danger.
<s>Reason for the which the anti-Islam stance of some current presidential candidates is so counterproductive.
<s>The terrorist issue is serious, and it deserves to be placed among the priorities of our intelligence and police services, our armed forces, and our diplomacy.
<s>It constitutes an important data point in our foreign policy.
<s>And it is essential to keep weapons of mass destruction out of reach of terrorists.
<s>But we must not fall into the trap laid by the terrorists.
<s>Do not fill the theater where the actions of thugs and criminals are carried out.
If we leave them the grand stage of our public discourse, we will diminish the quality of our civic life and divert our priorities.
Our strength would then be used against us.
